Stimuli for experiment on eu-es mixed DPs

Constraints, comments

  • Prefer items which are consistently recognisable in visual form.

  • For season-words (uda ‘summer’, negu ‘winter’), it would be possible to show four small landscapes with the target one highlighted and the rest faded-out.

  • Avoid lexical items with a clear cognate in Spanish (sega, hanka, botila…).

  • Avoid a-initial items (asto, hanka); the feminine -a from the det la can merge with the initial vowel, making it hard to determine the intended gender.

  • Many -u final roots are Latin loanwords from the 2nd declension (piku, mundu, putzu), which can explain, partially, why there are few with a Spanish feminine translation (esku, buru).

  • In some cases, the final phoneme of the root violates the phonotactics of Spanish, such as items ending in a palatal nasal (ezpain, mingain). These codas may trigger the det -a systematically, adding a confound.
